<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Reverse-Curl">Dumbbell Reverse Curl</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-reverse-curl" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell reverse curl</a> is an underrated exercise that targets your biceps, brachialis, and forearms. By switching to a pronated grip (palms down), you <a href="https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/physiology/articles/10.3389/fphys.2015.00215/full" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">increase activation of the brachioradialis</a>. This key forearm muscle helps bend your elbow, making it essential for many pulling movements.&nbsp;</p>



<p>This variation targets different muscles than a typical supinated grip (palms up), allowing for more balanced arm development. This exercise can improve overall arm strength, essential for advanced lifts and better performance in sports and daily activities. Additionally, it enhances grip strength, making it particularly beneficial for those looking to improve their deadlifts or other pulling movements.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Whether you&#8217;re working towards muscle definition or strength, this exercise should be a staple in your routine. Its versatility makes it effective for all fitness levels and prevents muscle imbalances by targeting different parts of your arm</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe title="04291201-Dumbbell-Standing-Reverse-Curl_Forearms_" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/976294896?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Dumbbell Reverse Curl Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Do</strong></h4>



<ol>
<li>Stand with feet shoulder-width apart, holding dumbbells in each hand.</li>



<li>Use an overhand grip with your palms facing down, and arms extended by your sides.</li>



<li>Keep your elbows close and curl the dumbbells until your forearms are parallel to the ground or slightly higher.</li>



<li>Lower the weights slowly and with control back to the starting position.</li>



<li>Repeat for the desired number of repetitions.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>Tips</strong></h4>



<ul>
<li>Maintain straight wrists throughout the movement to avoid strain.</li>



<li>Use a slow and controlled motion to fully engage the brachialis and brachioradialis.</li>



<li>Keep your elbows pinned to your sides for better isolation of the target muscles.</li>



<li>Start with lighter weights to build proper form before increasing intensity.</li>



<li>Avoid swinging the weights to focus on muscle engagement rather than momentum.</li>
</ul>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Optimal Sets And Reps</h4>



