<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Dumbbell-Incline-Bicep-Curl">Dumbbell Incline Bicep Curl</h3>



<p>The <a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/dumbbell-incline-bicep-curl" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">dumbbell incline bicep curl</a> primarily targets the long head of the biceps, giving better muscle length and overall fullness. What sets this exercise apart from the standard bicep curl is the positioning of the bench. </p>



<p>By setting the bench at an incline, your arms hang lower, providing a greater range of motion. This increased range stretches the biceps at the bottom and allows for a deeper contraction at the top.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Additionally, the incline reduces the involvement of other muscles and prevents momentum from aiding the lift. This means your biceps are forced to do more work, leading to better isolation and muscle growth.&nbsp;</p>



<p>An <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6977096/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">extended range of motion</a> enhances muscle activation, leading to overall improved muscle growth, strength, and performance. For anyone looking to build stronger, more defined arms, the dumbbell incline bicep curl is a great addition.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
